            if (opt.hasArg())
            {
                if (opt.getValues() == null || opt.getValues().length == 0)
                {
                    opt.addValueForProcessing(value);
                }
            }
            else if (!("yes".equalsIgnoreCase(value)
                    || "true".equalsIgnoreCase(value)
                    || "1".equalsIgnoreCase(value)))
            {
                // if the value is not yes, true or 1 then don't add the option to the CommandLine
                continue;
            }

            handleOption(opt);
            currentOption = null;
        }
    }
}
```

The problem is that in the `handleProperties` method, when processing an option from properties, it calls `handleOption(opt)` but it doesn't check if another option from the same option group has already been selected (either from command line args or from earlier properties).

Let me look at the `updateRequiredOptions` method to see how option group selection is handled:

Looking at this code:
```java
// if the option is in an OptionGroup make that option the selected option of the group
if (options.getOptionGroup(option) != null)
{
    OptionGroup group = options.getOptionGroup(option);

    if (group.isRequired())
    {
        expectedOpts.remove(group);
    }

    group.setSelected(option);
}
```

The issue is that the `handleProperties` method doesn't follow the same logic for determining if an option from a property should be eligible to be selected when another option in the group might have already been selected.

Actually, looking more carefully, the problem could be elsewhere. The `handleOption` method calls `updateRequiredOptions`, which does handle the group selection by calling `group.setSelected(option)`. This should properly handle option groups. 

But maybe the issue is that when we're processing options from properties, the option group's selected option is not being checked properly. Let me run the test again to see the specific error:

Now I'll implement the fix. The issue is in the `handleProperties` method where it doesn't consider if another option from the same group is already selected:

```java
private void handleProperties(Properties properties) throws ParseException
{
    if (properties == null)
    {
        return;
    }

    for (Enumeration e = properties.propertyNames(); e.hasMoreElements();)
    {
        String option = e.nextElement().toString();

        if (!cmd.hasOption(option))
        {
            Option opt = options.getOption(option);

            // Check if the option is part of a group and if another option is already selected
            OptionGroup group = options.getOptionGroup(opt);
            if (group != null && group.getSelected() != null)
            {
                // Another option in the group is already selected from command line,
                // so skip this option from properties
                continue;
            }

            // get the value from the properties
            String value = properties.getProperty(option);

            if (opt.hasArg())
            {
                if (opt.getValues() == null || opt.getValues().length == 0)
                {
                    opt.addValueForProcessing(value);
                }
